[[File:Anna Pessiak-Schmerling.jpg|thumb|Anna Pessiak-Schmerling, soprano Belle Brown and Bessie Brown]]
'''Anna Pessiak-Schmerling''' (1834 – 14 March 1896) was an [[Austrians|Austrian]] composer born in [[Vienna]].
==Life and career== She was born Anna Schmerling, daughter of Maria Anna Giannatasio del Río (1792-1868), and the granddaughter of Cajetan Giannatasio del Río (1764-1828) who had a boarding school in Vienna.<ref>{{cite book |title=Beethoven's letters: a critical edition : with explanatory notes, Volume 2|first=Ludwig|last=van Beethoven|first2=Alfred|last2=Christlieb Kalischer}}</ref> She studied with [[Mathilde Marchesi]] (1821-1913),<ref>{{cite journal|title=The Musical times, Volume 37|publisher=JSTOR|date=May 1, 1896|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=I-Z8gtxuC1kC&pg=PA338 |format=Digitized online by GoogleBooks|accessdate=28 November 2010}}</ref> and afterward worked as a professor of voice at the [[University of Music and Performing Arts, Vienna|Vienna Conservatory]]. She composed piano work and songs, and was noted for her masses and other sacred works.<ref>{{cite book |title=Woman's work in music: Being an account of her influence|author=Elson, Arthur|year=1903}}</ref>
[[Beethoven]] wrote the "Hochzeitslied" ("Wedding Song") for the wedding of Anna's mother to Leopold Schmerling in 1819.<ref>{{citation |url=http://www.beethoven-haus-bonn.de/sixcms/detail.php?id=15288&template=dokseite_digitales_archiv_en&_dokid=i3487&_seite=1-1|title= Cajetan Giannattasio del Rio, seine Ehefrau Katharina und seine Töchter Maria Anna und Franziska - Fotografien nach vier anonymen Silhouetten des 19. Jahrhunderts|accessdate=8 June 2014}}</ref> The Giannatasio del Rio family was associated with Beethoven through his nephew Karl, and Franziska (Fanny) Giannatasio del Río, Anna Pessiak-Schmerling's aunt, was a source for biographical detail on the composer. According to her, Beethoven wrote the song "Ruf vom Berge" for Anna's mother during an excursion to Himmel.<ref>{{citation |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=5eDTel9Px6gC&pg=PA74 |title=The Creative Process in Music from Mozart to Kurtag|author=Kinderman, William|page=74|accessdate=8 June 2014}}</ref>
