'''Julian Patrick''' (26 October 1927 - 8 May 2009) was an American [[opera]]tic [[baritone]] and [[voice teacher]]. Born in Mississippi, Patrick grew up in [[Birmingham, Alabama]] where he was a member of the [[Apollo Boys Choir]]. After graduating from the [[Cincinnati Conservatory of Music]], he began his professional career as a [[musical theatre]] performer in the 1950s; appearing in the original [[Broadway theatre|Broadway]] productions of ''[[The Golden Apple (musical)|The Golden Apple]]'' (1954), ''[[Bells Are Ringing (musical)|Bells Are Ringing]]'' (1956), ''[[Juno (musical)|Juno]]'' (1959), ''[[Once Upon a Mattress]]'' (1959), and ''[[Fiorello!]]'' (1959).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.playbill.com/news/article/129373-Julian-Patrick-Broadway-Actor-and-Opera-Singer-Dies-at-81|title=Julian Patrick, Broadway Actor and Opera Singer, Dies at 81|work=[[Playbill]]|author=[[Robert Simonson]]|date=19 May 2009|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111025194326/http://www.playbill.com/news/article/129373-Julian-Patrick-Broadway-Actor-and-Opera-Singer-Dies-at-81|archivedate=25 October 2011|df=}}</ref> He also studied singing privately in New York City with [[Cornelius L. Reid]].
After the 1950s Patrick worked mainly as a performer in operas, making appearances at the [[Dallas Opera]], the [[De Nederlandse Opera]], the [[Grand Théâtre de Genève]], the [[Houston Grand Opera]], the [[Lyric Opera of Chicago]], the [[Metropolitan Opera]], the [[Opéra national du Rhin]], the [[San Francisco Opera]], the [[Vienna Volksoper]], and the [[Welsh National Opera]] among other major opera houses.<ref name="obit"/> In 1968 he starred as Private Don Hanwell in the world premiere of [[Hugo Weisgall]]'s ''[[Nine Rivers from Jordan]]'' at the [[New York City Opera]].<ref name="nyt">{{cite web|url=https://select.nytimes.com/gst/abstract.html?res=FA0A15FC355C147493C2A8178BD95F4C8685F9&scp=51&sq=%22Hugo+Weisgall%22&st=p|title=Opera: 'Nine Rivers From Jordan' Has Premiere; City Troupe Performs Hugo Weisgall's Work Johnston Libretto Full of Religious Symbolism|author=[[Harold C. Schonberg]]|work=[[The New York Times]]|date=October 10, 1968}}</ref> He was particularly active with the [[Seattle Opera]] where he notably created the role of George Milton in the world premiere of [[Carlisle Floyd]]'s ''[[Of Mice and Men (opera)|Of Mice and Men]]'' in 1970. He also taught on the music faculty of the [[University of Washington]] for many years. He died at the age of 81 while on vacation in Santa Fe, New Mexico. He was survived by his life partner of 56 years, Donn Talenti.<ref name="obit">{{cite web|url=http://seattletimes.nwsource.com/html/obituaries/2009226351_obitpatrick16.html|title=Obituary: Julian Patrick, 81, famed baritone|work=[[Seattle Times]]|date=May 8, 2009|author=[[Melinda Bargreen]]}}</ref>
